{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500760"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:17:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:17:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1666"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1666"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.6,0.08,0.22,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83498"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1666"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68371"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"434"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2781"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28380"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83498"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with increased difficulty in reading. He has new reading glasses prescribed 12 months earlier, but things appear to have worsened considerably in the last few months. The TV is not as clear, and he cannot see the scoreboard scores at the oval. He finds it very uncomfortable visually to drive at night. In addition, he has noticed sunlight tends to adversely affect his vision much more than it used to. The patient has type 1 diabetes, but the optometrist one year ago said there was no evidence of diabetic changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E On Snellen chart testing, his visual acuity in both eyes is 6/18, and this is reduced to 6/24 when the background lighting is increased.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diabetic retinopathy","Cataracts","Open-angle glaucoma","Age-related macular degeneration","Corneal dystrophy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECataracts\u003C/strong\u003E, an opacification of the lens, are the most likely explanation for his symptoms, including the difficulty seeing in the presence of bright light, poor night vision, and reduced visual acuity. Diabetes mellitus can be complicated by changes to all ocular structures, with cataract being the most frequent complication to occur. There is an increased incidence of cataract formation in patients with diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough the patient has type 1 diabetes, \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetic retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to cause such visual disturbances, particularly as there were no diabetic changes one year ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen-angle glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E patients are usually asymptomatic and get peripheral vision loss before central vision loss. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge-related macular degeneration\u003C/strong\u003E first presents with visual distortion/metamorphopsia with later slow loss of central acuity in the common \u2018dry form\u2019 unless there is an acute sub-macular bleed (now the \u2018wet type\u2019).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003ECorneal dystrophy\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents at an earlier age (20s-30s).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cataracts are the most likely cause of bilateral gradual vision decline in the elderly.","Patients with cataracts often experience difficulty with night driving and increased sensitivity to bright lights."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders.","Nizami AA, Gurnani B, Gulani AC. Cataract. [Updated 2024 Feb 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539699/","Cicinelli MV, Buchan JC, Nicholson M, Varadaraj V, Khanna RC. Cataracts. Lancet. 2023 Feb 4;401(10374):377-389. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(22)01839-6. Epub 2022 Dec 21. PMID: 36565712. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36565712/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68371"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1666"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68371"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T20:26:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T20:30:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1666"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83498"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups